<section><title>Description</title>
<!--use <ref> on all component names (other than the one indexed from this file) in this section only-->
  <p>The <tag>award</tag><idx><tag>award</tag></idx> component defines conditions for awarding credit and evaluating user responses.  An <tag>award</tag> is the child of an <ref uri="https://www.doenet.org/#/content?tool=edit&doenetId=oqsskIj4WFljMigaogOCM"><tag>answer</tag></ref> and can be used to refine credit awarded when partial credit is desired. See examples below.</p>
</section> 

  
<section><title>Usage Examples</title>

<subsection><title>Example 1:  Using <tag>award</tag> to define two correct responses</title>
<p>In the sample code below, the <tag>award</tag> component is used to define two equally correct responses within an <ref uri="https://www.doenet.org/#/content?tool=edit&doenetId=oqsskIj4WFljMigaogOCM"><tag>answer</tag></ref> block.</p>

<example boxed="true"><title>Sample DoenetML code (Example 1)</title>

<pre>
&lt;p&gt;What is one possible value for &lt;m&gt;\sqrt{4}&lt;/m&gt; ?
  &lt;answer&gt;
    &lt;award&gt;sqrt(4)&lt;/award&gt;
    &lt;award&gt;-sqrt(4)&lt;/award&gt;
  &lt;/answer&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
</pre>
 
        </example>  
      </subsection>

<!--*******************************************************-->
 

<example><title>What Doenet Renders (Example 1)</title>
<p>What is one possible value for <m>\sqrt{4}</m> ?
  <answer>
    <award>sqrt(4)</award>
    <award>-sqrt(4)</award>
  </answer>
</p>
</example>


<!--******************************************************-->
    

<subsection><title>Example 2: Using <tag>award</tag> to define multiple responses with varying credit</title>

<p>In the sample code below, the <attr>credit</attr> attribute is employed to assign 50% credit to a close answer.  The <attr>symbolicEquality</attr> attribute is used with the <attr>simplifyOnCompare</attr> attribute to ensure acceptance of algebraically equivalent responses.  These attributes should be used together in combination when some flexibility in user input is desired (i.e. in this case, when <m>(x^2 + 3x + 2)</m> and <m>(2 + 3x + x^2)</m> are both acceptable).  
</p>

<example boxed="true"><title>Sample DoenetML code (Example 2)</title>
<pre>
Expand &lt;m&gt;(x+1)(x+2)&lt;/m&gt;:
          &lt;answer&gt;
            &lt;award symbolicEquality simplifyOnCompare&gt;
              &lt;math&gt;x^2+3x+2&lt;/math&gt;
            &lt;/award&gt;
            
            &lt;award credit="0.5" symbolicEquality simplifyOnCompare&gt;
              &lt;math&gt;x^2+2x+2&lt;/math&gt;
            &lt;/award&gt;
          &lt;/answer&gt;
</pre>
 
        </example>  
      </subsection>

<!--*******************************************************-->
 

<example><title>What Doenet Renders (Example 2)</title>
Expand <m>(x+1)(x+2)</m>:
          <answer>
            <award symbolicEquality simplifyOnCompare>
              <math>x^2+3x+2</math>
            </award>
            
            <award credit="0.5" symbolicEquality simplifyOnCompare>
              <math>x^2+2x+2</math>
            </award>
          </answer>
</example>
 

<!--******************************************************-->

<subsection><title>Example 3: Using <tag>award</tag> with <attr>expandOnCompare</attr></title>
<p>In the sample code below, the <attr>expandOnCompare</attr> attribute is used within the <tag>award</tag> block which allows Doenet to accept both <m>x^2 - 4</m> and <m>(x-2)(x+2)</m> as valid responses.  Partial credit is assigned to an answer with a sign error, and the <tag>award</tag> is given a <c>name</c> of <c>signError</c> in order to reference it later in a <ref><tag>feedback</tag></ref> block using the <attr>condition</attr> attribute.</p>

<example boxed="true"><title>Sample DoenetML code (Example 3)</title>
<pre>
&lt;graph&gt;
  &lt;curve&gt;x^2-4&lt;/curve&gt;
  &lt;point label="(2,0)"&gt;(2,0)&lt;/point&gt;
  &lt;point label="(-2,0)" labelPosition="upperleft"&gt;(-2,0)&lt;/point&gt;
  &lt;point label="(0,-4)" labelPosition="lowerleft"&gt;(0,-4)&lt;/point&gt;
&lt;/graph&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What function is graphed above?&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;m&gt;f(x) = &lt;/m&gt;&lt;answer&gt;
    &lt;award symbolicEquality expandOnCompare&gt;x^2-4&lt;/award&gt;
  &lt;award credit="0.25" name="signError"&gt;x^2+4&lt;/award&gt;
  &lt;/answer&gt;

  &lt;feedback condition="&dollar;signError"&gt;Check the sign of your
    answer.  What happens when you substitute &lt;m&gt;x=0&lt;/m&gt; 
    into your expression?&lt;/feedback&gt;

</pre>
 
        </example>  
      </subsection>

<!--*******************************************************-->
 

<example><title>What Doenet Renders (Example 3)</title>
<graph>
  <curve>x^2-4</curve>
  <point label="(2,0)">(2,0)</point>
  <point label="(-2,0)" labelPosition="upperleft">(-2,0)</point>
  <point label="(0,-4)" labelPosition="lowerleft">(0,-4)</point>
</graph>

<p>What function is graphed above?</p>
  <m>f(x) = </m><answer>
    <award symbolicEquality expandOnCompare>x^2-4</award>
    <award credit="0.25" name="signError">x^2+4</award>
  </answer>

  <feedback condition="$signError">Check the sign of your answer.  What happens when you substitute <m>x=0</m> into your expression?</feedback>
</example>



